<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1374,2011]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1518,1543]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is quite similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Gozmany, 1965" authorityName="Gozmany" authorityYear="1965" box="[732,1069,1518,1543]" class="Insecta" family="Tineidae" genus="Edosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyrochra">
<emphasis box="[732,865,1518,1543]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">E. pyrochra</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gozmany" box="[880,1061,1518,1543]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" refString="Gozmany, L. A. (1965) Some collections of tineid moths from Africa (Microlepidoptera). Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae, 11, 253 - 294." type="journal article" year="1965">
Gozmány, 
<number box="[1004,1061,1518,1543]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="1965.0">1965</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
in the male genitalia, but can be separated from the latter by the uncus lobe with distal half hooked, the valva having a very shallow ventral lobe, and the stouter aedeagus. Whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[569,702,1590,1615]" class="Insecta" family="Tineidae" genus="Edosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyrochra">
<emphasis box="[569,702,1590,1615]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">E. pyrochra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the uncus lobe is ensiform, the valva has a deep ventral lobe, and the aedeagus is slender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1374,2011]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1662,1687]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Description</emphasis>
. Adult (
<figureCitation box="[438,526,1662,1687]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 − 27" captionStartId="82.[151,264,1944,1966]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,224,1929]" captionTargetId="figure@82.[151,1436,193,1936]" captionTargetPageId="82" captionText="FIGURES 20 − 27. Adults of Edosa spp. 20, E. bicolor sp. nov., holotype, ♂; 21, E. subochraceella; 22, E. smithaella, ♂; 23, E. varians sp. nov., holotype, ♂; 24, E. aurea sp. nov., holotype, ♂; 25, E. torta sp. nov., holotype, ♂; 26, E. truncatula sp. nov., ♂; 27, E. hamata, sp. nov., holotype, ♂." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249840/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[494,526,1663,1687]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="27.0">27</number>
</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 12.0−12.5 mm in male. Head ochreous yellow. Antenna ochreous yellow, 0.9× length of forewing; scape with a few black pecten bristles; flagellum unicolorous. Labial palpus yellowish brown, second segment dark brown on outer surface. Thorax and tegula blackish brown. Forewing index 0.3, grayish black, individual scales uniformly colored; retinaculum present; cilia grayish black. Hindwing pale brownish gray, with a single short, slender evenly curved frenular bristle; cilia pale gray. Fore and mid legs blackish brown except tarsus yellowish brown mixed with black scales; hind leg yellowish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1374,2011]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Pregenital abdomen. In male, first tergum without sclerotization; coremata present in eighth segment; eighth sternite half as long as wide, without caudal process; eighth tergite trapezoidal, without caudal process.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1374,2011]" lastBlockId="20.[151,1437,151,680]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[379,465,1950,1975]" captionStart="FIGURES 57 − 59" captionStartId="89.[151,264,1942,1964]" captionTargetBox="[220,1379,215,1897]" captionTargetId="figure@89.[206,1381,193,1921]" captionTargetPageId="89" captionText="FIGURES 57 − 59. Male genitalia of Edosa spp. 57, E. truncatula sp. nov., holotype, slide No. YLL 11165 (57 a, aedeagus; 57 b, uncus lobes; 57, valva); 58, E. hamata sp. nov., holotype, slide No. YLL 11082; 59, E. robinsoni sp. nov., holotype, slide No. XYL 03174 (scale lines = 0.5 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/249847/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[433,465,1950,1975]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="58.0">58</number>
</figureCitation>
). Vinculum with anterior and posterior margins parallel sided; medial process absent from ventrocaudal margin. Tegumen about 0.6× depth of vinculum, trapezoidally concave at middle on anterior margin, convex at middle on posterior margin. Uncus with shouldered base touching each other, forming an heartshaped membraneous section with tegumen; uncus lobe 0.75× depth of vinculum, twisted at middle, basal half slightly expanded, punctate, distal half heavily sclerotized, hooked, smooth dorsally, hairy ventrally, apex narrowly rounded and melanized; sclerite absent between uncus lobes. Valva somewhat elongate triangular, narrowed basally, widest at 
<number box="[352,362,296,320]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[373,390,296,320]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="4.0">4</number>
, then narrowing to a large horn-like distal process; costal margin gently curved, unmodified; basal flange large, recurved, thumb-shaped; bridging lobe absent between basal flange and valva; ventral margin convex, forming very shallow ventral lobe; basal margin with digital ‘secondary apodeme’ close to apodeme; inner surface unmodified. Juxta angled caudally, short, flat, trapezoidal, about 0.3× length of aedeagus. Aedeagus stout, about 0.75× length of valva, basal 
<number box="[557,568,440,464]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[578,592,440,464]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="3.0">3</number>
being a pair of paddle-shaped structure, apex deeply concave at middle. Bulbus ejaculatorius 4.0× length of aedeagus, slightly expanded at base, where ductus ejaculatorius is slightly coiled; subdistal section not hypertrophied; distal section slightly expanded, semicircular.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,151,680]" box="[199,400,548,573]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Female unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
